<h2>Western Responses</h2>

<p>Western theology has not been indifferent to these concerns. Several responses have emerged over the centuries.</p>

<p>Thomas Aquinas argued that the <em>filioque</em> is theologically necessary: if the Spirit does not proceed from the Son, there is no way to distinguish the Spirit from the Son. Both would simply "come from the Father," with no distinguishing relation between them.</p>

<p>More recently, the Catholic Church has shown significant flexibility. The <em>Catechism of the Catholic Church</em> (§248) acknowledges the legitimacy of the Eastern formula and describes the difference as complementary rather than contradictory. Pope John Paul II, in his 1995 encyclical <em>Ut Unum Sint</em>, signaled openness to discussing the <em>filioque</em> as part of ecumenical dialogue. When the Pope celebrates liturgy with Eastern Catholics, the Creed is recited without the <em>filioque</em>.</p>

<p>Some Western theologians have gone further, arguing that the <em>filioque</em> should be removed from the Creed — not because it is heretical, but because it was added improperly and remains a stumbling block to unity. The Anglican Lambeth Conference of 1978 recommended its removal. Several Reformed theologians have made similar arguments.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— Joint Statement, North American Orthodox-Catholic Theological Consultation, 2003">
  The original form of the Creed, without the Filioque, should be normative for all Christians.
</Pullquote>

<h2>The Deeper Issue</h2>

<p>Behind the <em>filioque</em> controversy lies a larger question: How does the Church make doctrinal decisions? The East insists on conciliar consensus. The West (or at least the Catholic West) allows for papal authority to develop doctrine in ways that councils did not explicitly address.</p>

<p>The <em>filioque</em> is, in this sense, a test case for ecclesiology. It is not only about the Spirit's procession. It is about who has the right to define what Christians believe. Until that deeper question is addressed, the surface-level theological disagreement will remain unresolved.</p>

